Preheat your #oven to 200°C. Put the @water{300%ml} on to boil in a large #saucepan on medium heat. Add the @vegetable stock pot{1/2} and stir to dissolve.

While it comes to the boil, remove the root and dark green top from the @leek{1}, halve lengthways and slice into thin half moons. Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press). Halve, peel and finely chop the @red onion{1} into ½cm pieces.

Once your pan of stock is boiling, add the @couscous{150%g}, remove from the heat and cover with a #lid. Set it aside until everything else is ready.

Remove the stalk top from the @aubergine{1}, halve lengthways and chop into 1cm pieces. Place on a lined #baking tray, drizzle over some @olive oil{some} and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Toss to coat, then spread out evenly and roast on the top shelf of your #oven until soft and brown, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Heat a splash of @olive oil{some} in a #frying pan on medium-low heat. Add the leek, garlic and onion. Cook until soft, about ~{5%minutes}.

Stir in the @tomato purée{15%g} and @tomato passata{1.5%tbsp}. Continue to cook on low heat until the stew begins to thicken, ~{5-10%minutes}.

Add the @green olives{30}, a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a few grinds of @black pepper{some} to the stew. Once the aubergine is cooked, add that in too, along with the @ground almonds{15%g}.

Pick the @basil{1/2} leaves from their stalks and finely chop (discard the stalks). Take the lid off the couscous and fluff it up with a #fork. Stir through three-quarters of the basil.

Serve the basil couscous with the almond and aubergine stew on top. Crumble over the @feta cheese{1/2} and sprinkle on the remaining basil.

> Using nuts to thicken a sauce is a great trick to learn. It works for dishes from all around the world - Indian curries, Spanish soups, South American stews and many more. We're using almonds today to give a creamy texture and subtle flavour to this Greek-inspired stew. Served over herb-flecked couscous and topped with feta, you'd have to be nuts not to give it a go!